<font color="#FF0000">THANKS ARTHUR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Mar 12  2:53:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur,<br><br>
Thank you very much for welcoming my comments.  I confess<br>
I was worried that my comments might be unwelcome or at<br>
best considered irrelevant since I was not directly involved.  It was a relief to see your post, especially<br>
from somebody like you, a veteran and long contributor to this forum.  And I'm really glad you found some of my perspective valuable.<br><br>
Before I stumbled across this site I was visiting a site<br>
that had a searchable database of all the names on the wall.<br>
Since I don't know anybody who was killed in the war, I searched for all those from my hometown. The list came up with all these, 18, 19, 20 year olds from my town who had died, and it was really saddenning.  I live in Santa Cruz,<br>
CA, and all I could think of was how these kids should have been here surfing, not killing and being killed halfway around the world.  And I know they were not bad people, any more than the 18-20 year olds surfing here in Santa Cruz today are bad people.<br><br>
And again, I am sincerely thankful to you and all Vietnam<br>
Veterans for honorable service to our country.  Even though<br>
I was just an infant during the war, I know that you all<br>
were fighting for me and all citizens of America and for<br>
human rights in general.  I believe that if I had been a <br>
college student in the '60s, I would have been a vehement<br>
war protester.  But I would have been protesting the War,<br>
not the soldiers.  You were acting honorably out of your<br>
oath and your duty to your country.  It is the policy makers who I would have taken issue with.  I would have<br>
been struggling to get you all home as quickly as possible.<br>
We would have been on the same side, because I know all of <br>
you just wanted to come home (if all the Vietnam War movies are to be believed).  I believe that healing does happen and I hope that all vets who are still suffering to any degree will complete their healing soon, and this forum will probably be very helpful for that.<br><br>
Yes, take any group of people, and you can find some bad apples.  I'm sure there were a rotten few soldiers in Vietnam who did immoral things in war, just as there were a rotten few protesters who called you baby killers and spit on you.  I condemn the protesters who did that.  War is a terrible thing, but it seems the height of idiocy to try to blame war on the common soldier in the trenches!  I think today most of us understand this and properly honor and respect Vietnam War veterans (and I bet alot of people did back then too.  More than likely the media focused on the negative, controversial, sensational stuff--thank God we now have the Internet!)<br><br>
The only other thing that I wanted to say which I forgot to include in my original post, is that I believe the Vietnam War at least has one silver lining.  I believe that one of the things that made the Vietnam War different from others, here at home, was T.V. and modern communications in general.  The  images and body counts on the nightly news, something that was pretty much unprecedented, horrified civilians into action.  Ever since then, the government has had to be much more careful about making a case to the public before sending troops overseas.  This is one valuable legacy of the Vietnam War era, that we have both veterans and protestors to thank for.<br><br>
I know it must be hard to for Vietnam Vets to try to accept that the war was wrong, after their incredible courage and sacrifices.  But we must remember that the soldiers weren't wrong.  If anyone was wrong it was those who sent them into that battle.  If I had it my way, we'd cut out one or two of the Pentagon's hairbrained multi-billion dollar weapons reaserch programs and use the money to ensure that every Vietnam Veteran who actively participated in battle had a nice place to live and a good pension for life (isn't it the least we could do after what they've sacrificed and the personal risks they took for this country?), we'd eliminate all weapons exports, especially to undemocratic and/or unstable third-world nations, we'd cut back to a minimal military to protect our own borders only (until such a time as we had a *legitimate*  need to fortify), we'd throw all the corrupt and self-serving career politicians the hell out of Washington, and we'd all work together to move beyond war towards a true and lasting peace.<br><br>
What really frightens me is that it seems like all of this was being said in the '60s, but nothing has changed, in fact it in some ways it seems it has only gotten worse.  
<p><code>-- css@webcom.com  (Chris Schefler) </code><p>


